Here is a clear explanation of what is happening, plus two solutions:
âœ”ï¸ Option A: Make your Spring WebClient work with a proxy
âœ”ï¸ Option B: Make it work without a proxy

And Iâ€™ll also explain how to check the browser proxy configuration.

â¸»

âœ… 1. Why your proxy is NULL?

Your logs show:

http.proxyHost      = null
http.proxyPort      = null
https.proxyHost     = null
https.proxyPort     = null

This means your Linux server does NOT have any system proxy configured, so your WebClient will not use any proxy.

ğŸ‘‰ Your browser working does NOT mean your server has a proxy.
Browsers often use their own internal proxy settings (Firefox, Chrome, etc.), while Java uses system properties.

â¸»

âš¡ 2. OPTION A â€” Configure a proxy for Java (Spring WebClient)

If your environment requires a proxy, you must set JVM system properties, not browser settings.

âœ… 2.1. Pass proxy settings at startup

Run your Spring Boot app with:

java \
-Dhttp.proxyHost=YOUR_PROXY_HOST \
-Dhttp.proxyPort=YOUR_PROXY_PORT \
-Dhttps.proxyHost=YOUR_PROXY_HOST \
-Dhttps.proxyPort=YOUR_PROXY_PORT \
-jar your-app.jar

Example:

java \
-Dhttp.proxyHost=proxy.mycompany.local \
-Dhttp.proxyPort=8080 \
-Dhttps.proxyHost=proxy.mycompany.local \
-Dhttps.proxyPort=8080 \
-jar bankInfo.jar

OR in application.properties (Spring Boot 3+ automatically maps to system properties):

systemProp.http.proxyHost=proxy.mycompany.local
systemProp.http.proxyPort=8080
systemProp.https.proxyHost=proxy.mycompany.local
systemProp.https.proxyPort=8080


â¸»

âš¡ 3. OPTION B â€” Use WebClient WITHOUT PROXY

If your server has direct internet access, simply disable proxy configuration:

Change:

.proxy(spec -> {
    if (...) { ... }
    else { log.warn("No proxy configured in system properties"); }
})

Replace with:

// REMOVE proxy block entirely:
HttpClient httpClient = HttpClient.create()
        .responseTimeout(Duration.ofSeconds(10))
        .option(ChannelOption.CONNECT_TIMEOUT_MILLIS, 5000)
        .doOnConnected(conn ->
                conn.addHandlerLast(new ReadTimeoutHandler(10, TimeUnit.SECONDS))
                        .addHandlerLast(new WriteTimeoutHandler(10, TimeUnit.SECONDS))
        )
        .wiretap("reactor.netty.http.client.HttpClient",
                LogLevel.DEBUG,
                AdvancedByteBufFormat.TEXTUAL);

Then WebClient will connect directly.

â¸»

ğŸ“Œ 4. How to check your browser proxy configuration

Google Chrome / Chromium

Go to:

chrome://settings/system

Check if:
	â€¢	â€œUse system proxyâ€ is enabled
	â€¢	or manual proxy settings exist

Firefox

Go to:

about:preferences#general

Then â€œNetwork Settingsâ€.

âš ï¸ Your browser may use a proxy even if your Linux server does NOT.

â¸»

ğŸ” 5. How to test directly from server

Test without proxy

curl https://rest.sepatools.eu

If it works â†’ your WebClient should work without proxy.

Test with proxy (replace host & port)

curl -x http://proxy.mycompany.local:8080 https://rest.sepatools.eu

If this works only with proxy â†’ you must configure proxy in JVM.

â¸»

ğŸ‘ Summary

Situation	What to do
Browser works, Java does not	Browser uses proxy â†’ configure JVM proxy
Linux server can access internet directly	Remove proxy configuration in WebClient
You are unsure	Test using curl


